#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:9
msgid "Template string queries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:13
msgid ""
"Psycopg can process queries expressed as `template strings`__ defined in :"
"pep:`750` and implemented for the first time in Python 3.14."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:18
msgid ""
"Template strings are similar to f-strings__: they are string literals "
"interspersed with variables or expressions marked by ``{}``. They use a "
"``t`` prefix instead of ``f``, and can be used to express queries:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:24
msgid "cursor.execute(t\"SELECT * FROM mytable WHERE id = {id}\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:28
msgid ""
"The difference between the two is that f-strings are immediately evaluated "
"by Python and passed to the rest of the program as an already formatted "
"regular string; t-strings, instead, are evaluated by Psycopg, which has a "
"chance to process query parameters in a safe way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:33
msgid ""
"For example you can pass to a query some strings parameters, which may "
"contain unsafe characters such as ``'``, or come from untrusted sources such "
"as a web form, and leave Psycopg to perform the right processing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:37
msgid ""
"cursor.execute(\n"
"    t\"INSERT INTO mytable (first_name, last_name) VALUES ({first_name}, "
"{last_name})\"\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:43
msgid "This statement has the same effect as a classic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:45
msgid ""
"cursor.execute(\n"
"    \"INSERT INTO mytable (first_name, last_name) VALUES (%s, %s)\",\n"
"    (first_name, last_name),\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:52
msgid ""
"but has a clear readability advantage because the Python variable names or "
"expressions appear directly in the place where they will be used in the "
"query (no more forgetting to add a placeholder when adding a field in an "
"INSERT...)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:56
msgid ""
"If you want to convert the template string to a regular string, instead of "
"executing it directly, you can use the `sql.as_string()` or `~sql."
"as_bytes()` functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:60
msgid ""
">>> name = \"O'Reilly\"\n"
">>> dob = datetime.date(1970, 1, 1)\n"
">>> print(sql.as_string(t\"INSERT INTO tbl VALUES ({name}, {dob})\"))\n"
"INSERT INTO tbl VALUES ('O''Reilly', '1970-01-01'::date)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:67
msgid ""
"With template strings it is also easy to parametrize parts of the query "
"other than parameter values, for example tables or fields names:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:70
msgid ""
"cursor.execute(\n"
"    t\"INSERT INTO {table_name:i} (first_name, last_name) VALUES "
"({first_name}, {last_name})\"\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:76
msgid ""
"The ``:i`` specifies to merge `!table_name` to the query on the client using "
"the `identifier syntax`__ before continuing with the normal processing "
"(which might involve preparing the query, sending the parameters separately, "
"etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:84
msgid "Format specifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:86
msgid ""
"Format specifiers can be associated to template strings interpolation using "
"a ``:`` in the placeholder, for example in ``{id:b}``. Psycopg supports a "
"few format specifiers specifying :ref:`how to pass a parameter to the server "
"<binary-data>` and a few format specifiers specifying how to compose query "
"parts on the client, in a way similar to what can be obtained using the "
"`psycopg.sql` objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:93
msgid "The supported specifiers for parameter formats are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:95
msgid ""
"``s``: automatic parameter format, similar to using ``%s`` in a classic "
"query. This is the same effect of using no format specifier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:97
msgid ""
"``b``: use the binary format to pass the parameter, similar to using ``%b`` "
"in a classic query."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:99
msgid ""
"``t``: use the text format to pass the parameter, similar to using ``%t`` in "
"a classic query."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:102
msgid "The supported specifiers for query composition are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:104
msgid ""
"``i``: the parameter is an identifier_, for example a table or column name. "
"The parameter must be a string or a `sql.Identifier` instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:106
msgid ""
"``l``: the parameter is a literal value, which will be merged to the query "
"on the client. This allows to parametrize statements that :ref:`don't "
"support parametrization in PostgreSQL <server-side-binding>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:109
msgid ""
"``q``: the parameter is a snippet of statement to be included verbatim in "
"the query. The parameter must be another template string or a `sql.SQL`\\/\\ "
"`~sql.Composed` instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:120
msgid "Example: NOTIFY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:122
msgid ""
"The NOTIFY_ command takes a *channel* parameter (an identifier, so it must "
"be quoted with double quotes if it contains any non-alphanumeric character), "
"and a *payload* parameter as a string (which must be escaped with string "
"syntax, hence with single quotes)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:129
msgid ""
"The :sql:`NOTIFY` command cannot be parametrized by PostgreSQL, so it must "
"be composed entirely on the client side. Using template strings this could "
"be as simple as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:133
msgid ""
"def send_notify(conn: Connection, channel: str, payload: str) -> None:\n"
"    conn.execute(t\"NOTIFY {channel:i}, {payload:l}\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:138
msgid ""
"Calling the function with channel ``foo.bar`` and payload ``O'Reilly`` will "
"result in executing the statement ``NOTIFY \"foo.bar\", 'O''Reilly'``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:145
msgid "Example: nested templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:147
msgid ""
"A string template merges literal parts of the query with parameters. It is "
"also possible to pass templates to templates in order to compose more and "
"more complex and dynamic SQL statements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:151
msgid ""
"For example let's say we have an `!User` Python object mapping to an "
"``users`` database table. We might want to implement a `!search()` function "
"to return users by a list of ids, by names pattern, by group. This function "
"might be written as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:156
msgid ""
"def search_users(\n"
"    conn: Connection,\n"
"    ids: Sequence[int] | None = None,\n"
"    name_pattern: str | None = None,\n"
"    group_id: int | None = None,\n"
") -> list[User]:\n"
"    filters = []\n"
"    if ids is not None:\n"
"        ids = list(ids)\n"
"        filters.append(t\"u.id = ANY({ids})\")\n"
"    if name_pattern is not None:\n"
"        filters.append(t\"u.name ~* {name_pattern}\")\n"
"    if group_id is not None:\n"
"        filters.append(t\"u.group_id = {group_id}\")\n"
"    if not filters:\n"
"        raise TypeError(\"please specify at least one search parameter\")\n"
"\n"
"    joined = sql.SQL(\" AND \").join(filters)\n"
"    cur = conn.cursor(row_factory=class_row(User))\n"
"    cur.execute(t\"SELECT * FROM users AS u WHERE {joined:q}\")\n"
"    return cur.fetchall()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/tstrings.rst:180
msgid ""
"In this example we have used the `sql.SQL.join()` method overload that takes "
"a list of templates and returns a joined template in order to create an AND-"
"ed sequence of conditions."
msgstr ""

